                h2 DISCOVER A USER
                .sep.taller
                h3 The Problem
                p 
                    | Tran3D in essence is a 3D printing community where users design, prototype, sell and buy custom products and services. However, different users have different roles. Given a user,
                .flex.wider
                    ul
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right
                            span How can we distinguish his roles from others'?
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right 
                            span Which functions should we assign to him?
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right
                            span How can we help showcase his characteristics and develop his own "brand"?
                h3 The Analysis
                p 
                    span.highlight Upon discovering a user, one has to identify that person's roles and characteristics intuitively and efficiently.
                p
                    span.highlight Designers
                    |  productively transfer their concepts into printable designs. 
                    span.highlight Manufacturers
                    |  register 3D printers and promote their products. And like 
                    span.highlight the rest of individuals
                    | , both can follow, collect or purchase what they are interested in. According to this, I listed some keywords to guide my design.
                .flex.wider
                    ul
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right
                            span 
                                b Architecture
                                |—Interpreting underlying data structure and class inheritance reduces confliction between design and development.
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right
                            span
                                b Hierarchy
                                |—The item that first grabs the eye’s attention is at the top of the hierarchy. Each item that draws attention next is subordinate to the one before it.
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right
                            span
                                b Coloring
                                |—One of the easiest ways to distinguish objects is through colors.
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right
                            span
                                b Personalization
                                |—Users get motivated if they are provided with more personalized choices.
                h3 The Exploration
                img(src="assets/img/sketch.jpg").img--result
                p After sketching out several candidates, I made the following design decisions.
                h4 INFORMATION ARCHITECTURE
                p 
                    | I separated users into 
                    span.highlight three categories
                    | : common individuals, designers and manufacturers. All types shared a same template—Basic information was listed out; designs, collections, orders, followings and followers were organized into tabs. It is worth noting that designers were given an extra section to introduce their backgrounds, concepts and portfolios while manufacturers were given a shop page and a dashboard to manage printers, orders and etc.
        .level.level--tropical-blue
