                h2 MANAGE SHOP SERVICES
                .sep.taller
                h3 The Problem
                p 
                    | Tran3D manages and schedules 3D printing services based on 
                    span.highlight data and facts
                    | . It is important for manufacturers to provide authentic and intriguing data. This is a non-trivial work however: 
                .flex.wider
                    ol
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right
                            span Data encompasses various facets of 3D printing—There are printers, materials, colors and layout thicknesses, to name a few.
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right
                            span Pricing strategies are extremely complexe—The strategies vary from case to case and they are hard to understand if translated into mathematical model.
                p 
                    | Therefore 
                    span.highlight how can I help them upload the data in an intuitive way
                    |  and 
                    span.highlight how can I organize the data for a clearer reference
                    | ?
                h3 The Analysis
                p 
                    | To get better insights, I interviewed 8 people who own 3D printers. Based on their thoughts about products and marketing, I made 
                    span.highlight three personas
                    | .
                .board
                    h3 Manufacturer Persona
                    h4 Frank
                    p Frank, aged 32, is an assistant professor in material science at university. His lab owns 5 industrial 3D printers which could support more than 40 printable materials. Frank is very intelligent about 3D print technology and especially, he knows materials inside out. He is an expert in building mathematical models and experimenting new things.
                    h4 Sarah
                    p Sarah is a clerk at Tiertime, a 3D print company in Beijing. She works in service team to provide a chain of 3D print services. Since she is not an expert, her job is to maintain or update data provided by her technical colleagues. In order to deal with different platforms, Sarah needs to quickly understand interfaces and exchanging information with the team.
                    h4 David
                    p David is a technology enthusiast and he is only 20. His father bought him a desktop-level 3D printer on his last birthday, and he wants to make the full use of it. David knows how to use the printer however, he has no idea about how to provide 3D print service to others—He can only create simple pricing strategies but he is not sure if they would work. 
                p
                    | The personas reveal their 
                    span.highlight user needs
                    |  which can be described as:
                .flex.wider
                    ol
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right
                            span
                                b Hierarchical
                                |—It is easier to navigate and understand the system by organizing content hierarchically.
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right
                            span
                                b Standardized
                                |—Interactions are using the same paradigm so that users can understand.
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right
                            span
                                b Complete
                                |—More complete data increases a manufacturer's credibility, therefore popularity.
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right
                            span
                                b Intuitive
                                |—Uploading data is simple, not learned.
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right
                            span
                                b Flexible
                                |—The system allows manufacturers to manipulate, irrelevant to their backgrounds.
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right
                            span
                                b Foreseeable
                                |—Any preview of the outcome would help manufacturers circumvent mistakes, lowering the possibility of failed strategies.
                        li
                            i.icon.icon-li.ion-chevron-right
                            span
                                b Reversible
                                |—Data that is incorrect or outdated can be removed or modified.
                h3 The Exploration
                p During the design process, I tried to deliver the ideas above. Here, I will illustrate one by one:
                h3 1. Divide concepts into hierarchy.
                p A manufacturer may lack motivation to publish all service data in a single upload. So I divided the whole process and organized them into levels. From the comprehensive concept of shop to specific objects like printer and material, the hierarchical design would very much facilitate user flows.
        .level.level--swans-down
            .container
                img(src="assets/img/printer-management.png")
        .level
            .container
                h3 2. Unify layouts and interactions.
                p
                    | I chose to use a page component that had consistently shown up in Tran3D—
                    span.highlight the modal
                    | . This was because I did not want to overwhelm the user with an unfamiliar UI. A modal also made manufacturers concentrated on what they were doing. Within a modal, data uploading was splitted into steps and there was a top navigation bar indicating the progress. 
                h3 3. Include data that helps SEO and discoverability.
                p
                    span.highlight Titles, descriptions, tags, photos and categories
                    |  are properties for manufacturers to better describe their services. These features can be descriptive and educational to someone outside of their niches. Complete data speaks aloud for the services.
                h3 4. Utilize shapes and colors.
                p Making a pricing strategy is one of the most challenging problems in respect of interaction design—Strategies in 3D print industry involve a variety of factors, not only the physical properties but also labouring influences. 
                p
                    | A common mathematical model is 
                    span.highlight linear polynomial
                    |  which sums up a number of terms. The quantity of terms depends and terms are flexible since they have different interpretations. 
                p
                    | When I tried to illustrate this polynomial using simple shapes and colors, I found that 
                    span.highlight building a one-to-one correspondence between a term and a color
                    |  was the most intuitive solution. It turned a complex math formula into objects that can be easily cognized by human beings.
        .level.level--swans-down
            .container
                img(src="assets/img/formula.svg")
        .level
            .container
                h3 5. Add flexibility to the system.
                p
                    | The module must be adaptive to users with different backgrounds. Consider a user with non-expert background. He might need 
                    span.highlight notes
                    |  for terminologies, 
                    span.highlight tips
                    |  for interactions and 
                    span.highlight default values
                    |  for complicated data. On the contrary, an expert might need more specifications and details. And he wants to enable more terms in the polynomial to 
                    span.highlight better control
                    |  his pricing strategy.
                h3 6. Preview simulated results.
                p
                    | Manufacturers will get a 
                    span.highlight live preview
                    |  of what the price would be after proposing a pricing strategy. The result is calculated by applying the pricing strategy to a test case we provided. It even gives an instant feedback as the user make any adjustments to the linear polynomial. This functionality aims for manufacturers who want to find a suitable pricing strategy. It also makes them feel powerful so that they can trust our system.
                h3 7. Provide CRUD operations.
                p 
                    | Besides basic creating and reading, service data like printers, materials and even pricing strategies are 
                    span.highlight revisable
                    |  by manufacturers if they made any mistakes.
